\begin_layout Abstract
Applications such as computer graphics rendering, path planning for robotics
 and patch splitting algorithms greatly benefit from having an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses a given polynomial curve.
 Probably Bézier curves (which use the Bernstein basis) are the most common
 choice for this, since it is guaranteed that the curve is contained inside
 the convex hull of its control points.
 However, it is known that this convex hull is not the one with smallest
 volume, causing therefore great conservatism in all the applications mentioned
 before.
 This project derives and presents the MINVO basis, a polynomial basis that
 generates the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses any given polynomial curve.
 We show that the MINVO basis is able to obtain a volume that is 
\begin_inset Formula $2.36$
\end_inset

 times smaller for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $903$
\end_inset

 times smaller when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

.
 Global optimality is discussed and proven for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 using Sum-Of-Squares (SOS) Programming and moment relaxations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Supplementary material
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MATLAB code used for this project has been attached in the submission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bézier curves are extensively used in many different applications, which
 include computer aided design 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dimas19993d,de1999visualization,autodeskInventor,autodeskAutocad,autodeskMaya"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, simulations and animations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bargteil2014animation,roth1998bernstein"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and robotics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "park1995zier,faraway2007modelling,vskrjanc2010optimal,jolly2009bezier,tordesillas2019faster,preiss2017trajectory,sahingoz2014generation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, just to mention some.
 Many of these applications, specially those that need to check the intersection
 between two objects, make use of the convex hull property of the Bézier
 curves.
 This property allows to use the control points, instead of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ability to approximate the space occupied by a given polynomial curve
 with a polyhedron is crucial for many of these applications, specially
 those that need to check the intersection between two objects in real time.
 For instance, many path planning algorithms that use Bézier curves can
 easily ensure safety by ensuring the control points of the trajectory are
 inside the sequence of overlapping polyhedra that define the free space
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tordesillas2019faster,preiss2017trajectory,sahingoz2014generation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 This allows to obtain impose a finite number of convex constraints (of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x)\le0$
\end_inset

), instead of infinite constraints of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x,t)\le0\;\forall t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basis for the Bézier curves are the Bernstein polynomials, but, while
 they have some other useful properties, they are not designed to minimize
 the volume of the simplex that encloses a given interval of the curve.
 This directly translates into a great conservatism in many of the applications
 mentioned above.
 The goal of this project is to derive a polynomial basis that minimizes
 the volume of this convex hull.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This and is the one that enables real-time processing .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
imposing linear separability between the convex hull of its control points
 and an obstacle.
 , a sequence of overlapping polyhedra is usually generated in the free
 space, and then the constraint of the trajectory being in free space can
 be easily enforced by imposing that the control points of the associated
 Bezier curve or B-Spline are inside those polyhedra
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
, such as clipping methods, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "efremov2005robust,sederberg1990curve,schulz2009bezier"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contributions of this project are summarized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Global optimality proof for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 using SOS and moment relaxations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probably the paper most related to the problem this project is trying to
 solve is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herron1989polynomial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In that work, the authors imposed a ad-hoc form for the polynomials that
 form the basis, and then solved the optimization problem over the roots
 of those polynomials.
 They were able to find a local minimum (for that specific form of the polynomia
ls) for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 These project goes further, and tries to find global optimal solutions
 over all possible polynomials, and for higher degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar problem has also been studied in the hyperspectral unmixing of
 the remote sensing community, which consists of trying to find, in a given
 image pixel, the proportions (or abundances) of each macroscopic materials
 (endmembers) contained in that pixel 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uezato2019hyperspectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One way to address this problem is to find the simplex with minimum volume
 that encloses a set of points (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hendrix2013minimum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 However, the fact of dealing with many data points, and not necessarily
 distributed along a polynomial curve, leads to these works to generate
 different iterative algorithms to solve it (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rogge2006iterative,iordache2009unmixing,velez2003iterative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explicar convex hull algorithms?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other related works are 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kanazawa2014minimal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, that gives a bound for the volume of the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses a given convex body.
 
\end_layout

