\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex
\series default
: Convex hull of 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{0},...,\boldsymbol{v}_{n}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 These points are called the 
\series bold
vertexes
\series default
 of the simplex.
 The letter 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 will denote simplex, while 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 will denote the set of all possible 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simpleces.
 A simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is often characterized by its 
\series bold
matrix of vertexes
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}:=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\boldsymbol{v}_{0} & \cdots & \boldsymbol{v}_{n}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 A simplex whose vertexes are 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{0},\boldsymbol{e}_{1},\boldsymbol{e}_{2},...,\boldsymbol{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the vectors of the canonical basis, is called a
\series bold
 standard simplex
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Polynomial curve
\series default
 
\series bold
of degree
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
and dimension
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

: Parametric curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t):=\left[\begin{array}{c}
p_{0}(t)\\
\vdots\\
p_{k-1}(t)
\end{array}\right]:=\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(t)=\boldsymbol{c}_{i}^{T}\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 In this project, we will use the polynomial curves of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

 and we will refer to them simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

th order polyomial curve.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient matrix, and will be denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}:=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{c}_{0}^{T}\\
\vdots\\
\boldsymbol{c}_{k-1}^{T}
\end{array}\right]_{k\times n}\equiv\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\boldsymbol{p}_{n} & \cdots & \boldsymbol{p}_{0}\end{array}\right]_{k\times n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in the introduction, the goal of this project is to investigate
 the following optimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
definecolor{problem1_color}{RGB}{255,238,213}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
definecolor{problem2_color}{RGB}{255,233,233}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
definecolor{problem3_color}{RGB}{221,243,255}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
definecolor{problem4_color}{RGB}{240,255,229}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\backslash
fcolorbox{black}{problem1_color}{
\backslash
begin{minipage}[t]{1
\backslash
columnwidth - 2
\backslash
fboxsep - 2
\backslash
fboxrule}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Problem 1
\series default
: Given an 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

th order polynomial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

, find the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with minimum volume that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 In other words:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{S\in S^{n}}\quad f_{1}:=vol(S)\propto abs\left(\left|\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\boldsymbol{V}^{T} & \boldsymbol{1}\end{array}\right]\right|\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
s.t. & \boldsymbol{p}(t)\in S\quad\forall t\in[-1,1]\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{minipage}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, Problem 1 tries to find the triangle with the smallest area that contains
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
x(t) & y(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y(t)$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{nd}$
\end_inset

-degree polynomials.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, it tries to find the tetrahedron with the smallest volume that contains
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
x(t) & y(t) & z(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

(all 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{rd}$
\end_inset

-deg polynomials).
 Without loss of generality, we will assume throughout the paper that the
 polynomial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 is not contained in a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 , with 
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 this means that, for instance, the curve is not contained in a plane.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 is contained in a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

), then we can solve the problem by simply doing a change of variables and
 solve the problem directly in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that another way to intepret problem 1 is using the convex hull of
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

: the solution of problem 1 will give the smallest simplex that completely
 contains the convex hull of the polynomial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison_convex_hull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename src/imgs/comparison_convex_hull.png
	lyxscale 10
	width 70col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another way to interpret the MINVO basis is that it attempts to find the
 smallest simplex that completely contains the convex hull (shown in blue)
 of a polynomial curve (shown in red).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:comparison_convex_hull"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vskip-2ex
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As will be proven later in the report, Problem 1 is closely connected this
 other optimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\backslash
fcolorbox{black}{problem2_color}{
\backslash
begin{minipage}[t]{1
\backslash
columnwidth - 2
\backslash
fboxsep - 2
\backslash
fboxrule}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Problem 2:
\series default
 Given the vertexes 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{0},...,\boldsymbol{v}_{n}$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, find the 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

th order polyomial curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, whose coefficients vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{n},...,\boldsymbol{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 span a parallelogram with largest volume.
 In other words:
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\boldsymbol{p}(t)}\quad f_{2}:=-abs\left(\left|\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\boldsymbol{p}_{n} & \cdots & \boldsymbol{p}_{1}\end{array}\right]\right|\right)=-abs\left(\left|\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{P}\\
\boldsymbol{e}^{T}
\end{array}\right]\right|\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
s.t. & \boldsymbol{p}(t)\in S\quad\forall t\in[-1,1]\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{minipage}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the previous case, without loss of generality we will assume
 that the simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is non-degenerate.
 In other words, is not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equivalent Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now study the constraints and the objective functions of Problems
 1 and 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Constraints of Problem 1 and 2:
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Constraints-of-Problem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both problems share the same constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)\in S\quad\forall t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this constraint is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 being a convex combination of the vertexes 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the simplex for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{p}(t)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\lambda_{i}(t)\boldsymbol{v}_{i}\\
\sum_{i}\lambda_{i}(t)=1\quad\forall t\\
\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\quad\forall i,\forall t\in[-1,1]
\end{array}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th degree polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t):=\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{i}^{T}\boldsymbol{t},$
\end_inset

and matching the coefficients we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{P}=\boldsymbol{V}\underbrace{\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{0}^{T}\\
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{1}^{T}\\
\vdots\\
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{n}^{T}
\end{array}\right]}_{:=\boldsymbol{A}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we have also defined the 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)\times(n+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th row of this matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 contains the coefficients of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we can also write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{V}^{T}=\left(\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}\right)^{T}=\boldsymbol{A}^{-T}\boldsymbol{P}^{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric interpretation of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 is as follows.
 First note that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{p}(t)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\lambda_{i}(t)\boldsymbol{v}_{i}=\boldsymbol{v}_{n}+\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\lambda_{i}(t)\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{i}-\boldsymbol{v}_{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining now
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 as the normal vector to the hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

 formed by the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

,...,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{n-1}$
\end_inset

, and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}^{T}\boldsymbol{p}(t)\ge0$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 pointing towards the interior of the simplex), we have that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
dist\left(\boldsymbol{p}(t),\boldsymbol{\pi}\right):=\left(\boldsymbol{p}(t)-\boldsymbol{v}_{n}\right)^{T}\boldsymbol{n}=\\
\\
=\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}\lambda_{i}(t)\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{i}-\boldsymbol{v}_{n}\right)^{T}\boldsymbol{n}=\lambda_{0}(t)\;dist\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{0},\boldsymbol{\pi}\right)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{0}(t)=\frac{dist\left(\boldsymbol{p}(t),\boldsymbol{\pi}\right)}{dist\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{0},\boldsymbol{\pi}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar reasoning applies for the other 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents the ratio between the distance of the curve to the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

 (formed by the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}\;,j\neq i$
\end_inset

) and the distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 to that plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Geometric-interpretation-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename src/imgs/geom_meaning_lambdai_modified.pdf
	lyxscale 130
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Geometric interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 represents the distance between the vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the plane formed by the vertexes 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}\;\;i\neq j$
\end_inset

, normalized with the distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 to that plane (left).
 For a standard simplex in 3D (right), the curve in red is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\lambda_{1}(t) & \lambda_{2}(t) & \lambda_{3}(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Geometric-interpretation-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vskip-2ex
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally note that the second constraint can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{1}=\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}^{T}\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}=\boldsymbol{1}^{T}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Objective Function of Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the previous relationships, note that, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\boldsymbol{V}^{T} & \boldsymbol{1}\end{array}\right]\right|=\left|\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\boldsymbol{A}^{-T}\boldsymbol{P}^{T} & \boldsymbol{1}\end{array}\right]\right|=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\left|\boldsymbol{A}^{-T}\right|\left|\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{P}^{T}\underbrace{\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{1}}_{=\boldsymbol{e}^{T}}\end{array}\right]\right|\propto\left|\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}\right|=\frac{1}{|\boldsymbol{A}|}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where in the last step we have used the fact that everything inside the
 second determinant is given (i.e.
 not a decision variable of the optimization problem), and the fact that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|=\left|\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\propto\frac{1}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}|\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 We can therefore maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $abs(\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|)$
\end_inset

, or, equivalently, minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $-abs\left(\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Objective Function of Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly to the previous subsection, we have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{P}\\
\boldsymbol{e}^{T}
\end{array}\right]\right|=\left|\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{V}\\
\underbrace{\boldsymbol{e}^{T}\boldsymbol{A}^{-1}}_{=\boldsymbol{1}^{T}}
\end{array}\right]\boldsymbol{A}\right|\propto\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}\propto-abs\left(\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equivalent Formulation for problem 1 and 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we can solve problem 1 (or problem 2 respectively) for 
\series bold
any
\series default
 given polynomial curve (any given simplex) by solving the following problem:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\backslash
fcolorbox{black}{problem3_color}{
\backslash
begin{minipage}[t]{1
\backslash
columnwidth - 2
\backslash
fboxsep - 2
\backslash
fboxrule}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Problem 3: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\boldsymbol{A}}\quad f_{3}:=-abs\left(\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
s.t. & \boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{t}\ge\boldsymbol{0}\quad\forall t\in[-1,1]\\
 & \boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{1}=\boldsymbol{e}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{minipage}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Problem 3 is nonconvex, since the objective function is the determinan
t of a non-symmetric matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use now Sum-Of-Squares programming, which is an 
\emph on
if and only if 
\emph default
condition for univariate polynomials to rewrite the second constraint of
 problem 2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parrilo09"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\;\;\forall t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}^{T}\left((t+1)\boldsymbol{W}_{i}+(1-t)\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\right)\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}\\
\boldsymbol{W}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n+1}{2}},\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n+1}{2}}
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\;\;\forall t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Cuidado que ahora no puedo sacar factor comun a t_hat (pues son de different
 size)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}^{T}\boldsymbol{W}_{i}\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}+\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}^{T}(t+1)(1-t)\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}\\
\boldsymbol{W}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n}{2}+1},\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n}{2}}
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the 
\emph on
if and only if
\emph default
 condition applies because it is a univariate polynomial 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parrilo09"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We end up therefore with a nonconvex finite-dimensional optimization problem,
 where the decision variables are the positive semidefinite matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{W}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[0,n]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No generality has been lost in problem 3.
 However, one disadvantage is that it easily becomes intractable for larger
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 To make it more tractable, we can try to reduce the number of decision
 variables of Problem 4 by imposing an structure in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 As Problem 1 is trying to minimize the volume of the simplex, we can impose
 that the planes of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex be tangent to the curve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zhou2002algorithms,klee1986facet"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Using the geometric interpretation of these 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 given in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Constraints-of-Problem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this means that each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 should have either real double roots (places where the curve is tangent
 to the plane), and/or roots at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 This translates into the formulation shown in Problem 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{figure}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\backslash
fcolorbox{black}{problem4_color}{
\backslash
begin{minipage}[t]{1
\backslash
columnwidth - 2
\backslash
fboxsep - 2
\backslash
fboxrule}%
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Problem 4:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\boldsymbol{A}}\quad f_{4}:=-abs\left(\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s.t:
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=-b_{i}(t-1)\stackrel[j=1]{\frac{n-1}{2}}{\prod}(t-t_{j})^{2}\quad i=0,2,...,n-1\\
\lambda_{i}(t)=\lambda_{n-i+2}(-t)\quad\quad\quad i=1,3,...,n\\
b_{i}\ge0\quad i=0,2,...,n-1\\
\sum_{i=0}^{i=n}\lambda_{i}(t)=1
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even:
\series default
\bar default
 define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{a}$
\end_inset

 the set of odd integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\in\left[0,\frac{n}{2}-1\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{b}$
\end_inset

 the set of even integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\in\left[0,\frac{n}{2}-1\right]$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{a}:=2,4,..,\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{b}:=1,3,..\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

Cuidado que n/2 esta incluido o no si n/2 es odd o even
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=-b_{i}(t+1)(t-1)\stackrel[j=1]{\frac{n-2}{2}}{\prod}(t-t_{j})^{2}\quad i\in\mathcal{I}_{a}\\
\lambda_{i}(t)=b_{i}\stackrel[j=1]{\frac{n}{2}}{\prod}(t-t_{j})^{2}\quad\quad\quad i\in\mathcal{I}_{b}\\
\lambda_{j}(t)=\lambda_{n-i+1}(-t)\quad\quad\quad i=\frac{n}{2}+1,...,n\\
b_{i}\ge0\quad i\le\frac{n}{2}\\
\sum_{i=0}^{i=n}\lambda_{i}(t)=1
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

 is odd (
\begin_inset Formula $n=2,6,10...)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{i}(t)=-b_{i}(t+1)(t-1)\stackrel[j=1]{\frac{n-2}{4}}{\prod}(t-t_{j})^{2}(t+t_{j})^{2}\quad\quad i=\frac{n}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{n}{2}$
\end_inset

 is even (
\begin_inset Formula $n=4,8,12...)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{i}(t)=b_{i}\stackrel[j=1]{\frac{n}{4}}{\prod}(t-t_{j})^{2}(t+t_{j})^{2}\quad\quad i=\frac{n}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that, as the feasible set of Problem 4 is contained in the feasible
 set of Problem 3, every local minima of Problem 4 is also a local minima
 of Problem 3 THIS IS FALSE I THINK
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{minipage}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{figure}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between Problems 1, 2, 3 and 4 is given in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:relationships_problems"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 First note that the structure imposed for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 in Problem 4 guarantees that they are nonnegative for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the feasible set of Problem 4 is contained in the feasible set of
 Problem 3 or, in other words, any feasible solution of Problem 4 is feasible
 for Problem 3 (the converse is not true in general).
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}^{*}\le f_{4}^{*}$
\end_inset

 holds.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

 found in Problem 3 or 4 can be used to find the vertexes of the simplex
 in Problem 1 (by simply using 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}^{*}=\boldsymbol{P}\left(\boldsymbol{A}^{*}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient matrix of the polynomial given), or to find the polynomial
 matrix in Problem 2 (by using 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}^{*}=\boldsymbol{V}\boldsymbol{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}$
\end_inset

 contains the vertexes of the simplex given).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename src/imgs/relationships_problems.pdf
	lyxscale 130
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relationship between Problems 1, 2, 3 and 4: Problem 4 and Problem 3 have
 the same objective function, but the feasible set of Problem 4 is contained
 in the feasible set of Problem 3, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}^{*}\le f_{4}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Both Problem 3 and 4 generate a (potentially locally) optimal solution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

, which can be applied to any polynomial curve to find the simplex in Problem
 1, or to any simplex to find the polynomial curve in Problem 2.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:relationships_problems"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vskip-2ex
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization Problems 2 and 3 have been solved using the nonconvex solvers
 IPOPT 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wachter2006implementation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Knitro 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "byrd2006k,byrd1999interior"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (for Problem 3), the fmincon nonconvex solver 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "matlabOptToolbox"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (for Problem 4), and the Yalmip 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lofberg2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 interface.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We were able to find local minima for Problem 4 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4,5,6,7$
\end_inset

, and the same local minima were found in Problem 3 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 (Problem 3 becomes intractable for higher 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 The optimal matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 found are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table_matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that any permutation in the rows of A will also be a minimizer (since
 only the sign of the determinant is affected).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding plots of the basis functions are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:minvo_and_bernstein"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, together with the Bernstein basis and the Lagrange basis for comparison.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One natural question to ask is whether the basis found constitutes a global
 minimizer either for Problem 3 or Problem 4.
 To answer this, first note that both Problem 3 and Problem 4 are polynomial
 optimization problems.
 Therefore, we can make use of Lasserre's moment method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lasserre2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and increase the order of the moment relaxation to find tighter lower
 bounds of the original nonconvex polynomial optimization problem.
 Using this technique, we were able to obtain the same objective value (proving
 therefore global optimality) for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 (in Problem 4), and for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 (in Problem 3).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results lead us to the following conclusions (also summarized in Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table_matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 is a global minimizer of both Problem 3 and Problem 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2,3,4$
\end_inset

 are global minimizers for Problem 4, and at least local minimizers for
 Problem 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5,6,7$
\end_inset

 are at least local minimizers for Problem 4, and are at least feasible
 solutions for Problem 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table_matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is also shown the ratio 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{B}|\right)}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}|\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{B}$
\end_inset

 denote the associated matrices for the MINVO and Bernstein basis respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us know analyze the meaning of these results in both for the Problems
 1 and 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From the point of view of Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Problem 1 attempts to find the simplex with smallest volume the encloses
 a given polynomial curve.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison2d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 it is shown the simplex found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, and in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison3d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 The simplex found using the Bernstein basis is also shown for comparison.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{B}$
\end_inset

 denote the simpleces that the MINVO and Bernstein basis generate respectively,
 we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{vol\left(S\right)}{vol\left(S_{B}\right)}=\frac{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{B}|\right)}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}|\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means, for instance, that for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, the MINVO basis finds a simplex that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx2.36$
\end_inset

 smaller than the one the Bernstein basis finds.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

, the MINVO basis is able to obtain a simplex that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx903$
\end_inset

 times
\series bold
 
\series default
smaller than the one achieved using the Bernstein basis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From the point of view of Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In problem 2, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is given, and we obtain the polynomial curve that is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, whose coefficients vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{n},...,\boldsymbol{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 span a parallelogram with largest volume.
 The results for a regular triangle and a tetrahedron (
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

) are shown in Figs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison2d_simplex_given"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:comparison3d_simplex_given"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 respectively).
 Similar to the previous case, let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{B}$
\end_inset

 denote the parallelograms that the MINVO and Bernstein basis generate respectiv
ely, we have that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{vol\left(P_{B}\right)}{vol\left(P\right)}=\frac{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}_{B}|\right)}{abs\left(|\boldsymbol{A}|\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which means that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, the MINVO basis finds a parallelogram 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx2.36$
\end_inset

 times bigger than the Bernstein basis (
\begin_inset Formula $\approx903$
\end_inset

 times bigger for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As we can see from the figures, the polynomial generated by the MINVO basis
 occupies much more space than the one generated using the Bernstein polynomial.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename src/imgs/comparison2d_simplex_given.pdf
	lyxscale 130
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

