\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Results for the MINVO basis.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 denotes the coefficient matrix of the MINVO basis (i.e.
 each polynomial in the basis is given by the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

), while 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}_{B}$
\end_inset

 represents the matrix of the Bernstein basis (
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 for both).
 The bigger the absolute value of the determinant, the smaller the associated
 simplex (for Problem 1) and the smaller the parallelogram (for Problem
 3).
 These matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 are independent of the polynomial curve given (in Problem 1), or of the
 simplex given (in Problem 2).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:table_matrices"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename src/imgs/plots_basis.pdf
	lyxscale 130
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Comparison between the MINVO, Lagrange and Bernstein basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4,5,6,7$
\end_inset

.
 All these basis satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=0}^{i=n}\lambda_{i}(t)=1$
\end_inset

, and the MINVO and Bernstein basis also satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\;\forall t\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:minvo_and_bernstein"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
vskip-2ex
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions and Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work derived and presented the MINVO basis.
 The key features of this basis is that it finds the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-simplex that encloses a given polynomial curve (Problem 1), and also finds
 the polynomial curve that is inside a given simplex, and whose coefficient
 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{n},...,\boldsymbol{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 generate a parallelogram with largest volume (Problem 2).
 Global Optimality was also proven for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exciting results of this project naturally lead to the following questions
 and conjectures:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is the global optimum of Problem 3 the same as the global optimum of Problem
 4? In other words, are we losing generality by imposing the specific structure
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

?.
 The results seem to indicate that it is likely that no generality is lost.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does there exist an analytical solution (i.e.
 not numerical) for Problem 3 for any degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does there exist a recursivity formula to obtain the solution of problem
 3 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 given the previous solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $1,...,n-1$
\end_inset

? Would this recursivity formula allow to easily prove global optimality
 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of Problem 3?
\end_layout

