Upper-case bold letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 will represent matrices, while lower-case bold letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 will represent column vectors.
 
\begin_inset Formula $conv(M)$
\end_inset

 will represent the convex hull of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cdot|$
\end_inset

 will represent the determinant operator, and the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto$
\end_inset

 will represent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proportional to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot_{k\times n}$
\end_inset

 will denote the size of a matrix (rows 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 columns).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

 will denote a column vector of ones of appropriate size.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\ge\boldsymbol{b}$
\end_inset

 will denote an element-wise inequality.
 Let us also denote the define the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}:=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 1\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $abs(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 will represent the absolute value.
\end_layout

